ern state since World War II. In so doing, they illustrate the distinctive rationality and logics of contemporary capitalism while calling for a politics based on collective institutions that exist outside the state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aCapitalismxPolitical aspects. 0aCapitalismxSocial aspects. 0aEconomic development. 0aGlobalization. 0aLabor. 0aPostcolonialismxEconomic aspects. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh1 aNeilson, Brett, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478003267zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478003267423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478003267.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles